HEADWORD: Thole
<hw>Thole</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tholed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tholing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>⟦thorn⟧olen</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧olien</ets>, AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧olian</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>thol⟦omac⟧n</ets>, OHG. <ets>dol⟦emac⟧n</ets>, G. ge<ets>duld</ets>
patience, <ets>dulden</ets> to endure, Icel. <ets>⟦thorn⟧ola</ets>, Sw.
<ets>t⟦aring⟧la</ets>, Dan. <ets>taale</ets>, Goth.
<ets>⟦thorn⟧ulan</ets>, L. <ets>tolerate</ets>, <ets>tulisse</ets>, to
endure, bear, <ets>tollere</ets> to lift, bear, Gr. <?/ to bear, Skr.
<ets>tul</ets> to lift. ⟦root⟧55. Cf. <er>Tolerate</er>.]</ety> <def>To
bear; to endure; to undergo.</def> <mark>[Obs. or Scot.]</mark>
<rj><au>Gower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So much woe as I have with you <qex>tholed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>thole</qex> the winter's steely dribble.</q>
<rj><qau>Burns.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

